because we can be more objective about it

00:14:28.980 --> 00:14:30.140
because if we ask it about code,

00:14:30.190 --> 00:14:31.120
then it gets a little too close.

00:14:31.450 --> 00:14:32.960
But I think there's analogies.

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:36.980
Do you think LLMs will undercut

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:39.620
foundational beginning scientists?

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:41.240
If you have a scientist coming along,

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:48.760
are they just going to use llms and not develop really deep thinking ways to deeply think about

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:54.060
scientific principles and do scientific research and just leverage on asking these ais too much and

00:14:54.580 --> 00:14:58.860
do you think that's going to erode the foundation of science or programming you know

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:08.180
asking for a friend all of you just ask it for a friend have a a potential to change the ecosystem

00:15:08.220 --> 00:15:17.500
But I've been in paradigm shifts before, and there were the similar kind of conversations when the World Wide Web or the cell phone came out, personal computers.

00:15:18.420 --> 00:15:33.240
And I think, you know, LLMs do a good job on information that they have been trained with and to predict the next word or the next token, if you will.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:40.780
And I think science is very much like at a lot of sciences at a different level.

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:43.700
Like, how do I think about things?

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:51.280
What do I posit on something that is unknown and how do I prove it?

00:15:52.030 --> 00:16:00.220
And I think what we're seeing is, yes, the LLMs are getting better and better at spitting back what they know,

00:16:00.440 --> 00:16:05.960
particularly if you go out and search other corpuses of data.

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:11.120
